On Sun, 10 Jan 1999, Steve Gardner wrote:

> Andre Engels wrote:
> >
> >Steve Gardner wrote:
> >
> >> I live in Australia, where the various states follow different policies
> >> regarding daylight savings. Victoria, where I live, has daylight
> >> savings, and I like it a lot, since it transfers an hour of daylight
> >> from the morning where I have little use for it, to the evening where I
> >> really enjoy it.
> >
> >In my opinion, the main problem with Daylight Savings Time is the change
> >that occurs twice a year. If it's so nice to have Daylight Savings Time in
> >Summer, is it really so harmful to have it in Winter as well?
> 
> It would be most unpleasant to have daylight savings in winter. It would
> mean that it would still be dark at 9 in the morning! In the winter
> you want more light in the morning, in the summer, more light in the
> evening.
> 
Not to mention that it would completely destroy the basis of our
chronology: that noon is the time the sun crosses thes meridian. One
might as well just shift all times back by one hour.




